ce:section.ce:para:
The ultraviolet–visible (UV–Vis) and photoluminescence (PL) spectra of copper nanoclusters (CuNCs) and CDNCs (Scheme 1
                        ) in aqueous media were recorded in a given wavelength range (Fig. 1
                        a). The absorption and emission maxima originated from CuNCs and CDNCs, rather than CS and CD (Fig. 1a), and this was confirmed using the absorption and PL spectra of the pristine materials (Fig. S1). The PL intensity of the as-synthesized CuNCs was weak; this was mainly attributed to the presence of a high concentration of Cu2+ ions owing to the weak reducing ability of CS [29]. After the in-situ addition of CD during the synthesis of CuNCs, we have determined that the PL intensity of the modified nanoclusters i.e., CDNCs increased yet the excitation and emission wavelengths were unchanged (Fig. 1 and S1). The digital photographs of aqueous solutions of the as-prepared CDNCs (inset of Fig. 1a) further confirmed their strong green PL emission, under 365 nm UV irradiation. Moreover, aqueous solutions of the as-prepared CDNCs were colorless under visible light [30]. Furthermore, no visible resonance absorption peaks were observed, which indicated that the product consisted of nanoclusters and no copper nanoparticles (CuNPs) formed during synthesis [31].
